abstract: The broadcaster, whose father had Alzheimer’s, announced the creation of a center in Houston that will research treatment and care for people with neurological diseases.
snippet: The broadcaster, whose father had Alzheimer’s, announced the creation of a center in Houston that will research treatment and care for people with neurological diseases.
lead_paragraph: Jim Nantz had a master plan: his father would retire from his furniture business and join him on the road at N.F.L. games, golf tournaments and college basketball arenas. The elder Nantz, who was also named Jim, would help manage and organize his son’s busy life on the road.

abstract: Christopher Bailey’s rejiggered proportions, his lean woolen trousers, his shearling jackets, and his floaty lumberjack jackets looked cool enough that one forgave the fur wife-beater undershirts.
snippet: Christopher Bailey’s rejiggered proportions, his lean woolen trousers, his shearling jackets, and his floaty lumberjack jackets looked cool enough that one forgave the fur wife-beater undershirts.
lead_paragraph: MILAN — An artificial rain shower ended the Burberry Prorsum show Saturday evening, pelting the models in their flasher-ready, see-through slickers and splashing all the front-row types, who had to pull up their knees. It called to mind the horror of a character Mink Stole played in John Waters’s “Desperate Living.” “You know I hate nature!” she shrieked to her housekeeper, who had made the error of driving the family Mercedes through a Baltimore park.

abstract: Key Porter Books, a prominent Canadian publishing house in Bolton, Ontario, announced it would temporarily suspend publishing operations, The Globe and Mail of Toronto reported.
snippet: Key Porter Books, a prominent Canadian publishing house in Bolton, Ontario, announced it would temporarily suspend publishing operations, The Globe and Mail of Toronto reported.
lead_paragraph: Key Porter Books, a prominent Canadian publishing house in Bolton, Ontario, announced it would temporarily suspend publishing operations, The Globe and Mail of Toronto reported. The company, which releases around 100 books a year, laid off almost two-thirds of its staff members in September and said on Friday that it would halt production of all new titles. It would continue to market and distribute books already in print and would consider restructuring options, according to a company statement. “Key Porter Books has played a leading role in giving a voice to the Canadian story, and we will do everything possible to ensure that voice continues to be heard,” Jordan Fenn, the vice president and publisher, said in the statement. Several authors and literary agents have expressed concern over the status of their books and frustration with the company’s lack of communication. Julie Devaney, who planned to have her first book released by Key Porter in April, told The Globe and Mail that finding “as good of a fit” with another publisher would be difficult. Key Porter was founded by the author and publisher Anna Porter as a joint venture with Key Publishers in 1979 and acquired by H. B. Fenn & Company in 2004. It has represented authors including Margaret Atwood, Joan Barfoot and Conrad Black.
